The available scientific literature shows no significant link between vitamin D deficiency and the development of osteochondritis dissecans; instead, this condition stems mainly from localized blood flow issues, repetitive microtrauma, or excessive physical activity affecting joints—factors unrelated to systemic nutritional deficits such as those seen in hypovitaminosis D. Although adequate vitamin D supports overall skeletal integrity through proper calcium absorption and bone maturation, absence of data connecting deficient serum concentrations specifically to cartilage necrosis or fragmentation underpins the conclusion that vitamin D insufficiency plays an indirect if any role beyond basic structural support.

